{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4521d78c-a57d-4325-8f95-f38ea5ea527b","content":"Use **dotnet-trace** — it's the go-to tool for .NET CPU profiling and requires no install beyond the .NET SDK.\n\n### Quick steps\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (uses the cpu-sampling profile by default)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### If you need OS-level detail\n\nUse **PerfView** directly — it captures both managed and native call stacks via ETW:\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect /CircularMB:500 /ThreadTime /MaxCollectSec:30\n```\n\n### Which to pick?\n\n| Tool | Best for |\n|---|---|\n| `dotnet-trace` | Quick managed-code hotspot analysis, low overhead |\n| **PerfView** | Deep analysis including native code, GC, kernel events |\n\nFor a 100% CPU scenario, start with `dotnet-trace` — the 30-second sample will show you which methods are burning CPU. Escalate to PerfView if the hot path crosses into native/OS code.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"56933b98-ece4-4499-8adc-6b1d1771ec9a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I can answer this from knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":417,"requestId":"D805:11233D:E7E721:10A4D24:69F2AFAD"},"id":"9da09390-81da-4ac5-87c9-5f9146a15afa","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:26:16.679Z","parentId":"ab28a0a8-cd17-42ae-96ec-910ee9926bd8"}
